Optimal Transport with Linear Programming¶

Important: Please read the installation page for details about how to install the toolboxes.

This numerical tours details how to solve the discrete optimal transport problem (in the case of measures that are sums of Diracs) using linear programming.

You need to install CVXPY. Warning: seems to not be working on Python 3.7, use rather 3.6.

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import cvxpy as cp

Optimal Transport of Discrete Distributions¶

We consider two dicretes distributions

α=∑i=1naiδxiandβ=∑j=1mbjδyj.α=∑i=1naiδxiandβ=∑j=1mbjδyj.

where n,mn,m are the number of points, δxδx is the Dirac at location x∈Rdx∈Rd, and (xi)i,(yj)j(xi)i,(yj)j are the positions of the diracs in RdRd.

Dimensions (n,m)(n,m) of the coulds.

In [2]:
n = 60
m = 80

Generate the point clouds X=(xi)iX=(xi)i and Y=(yj)jY=(yj)j.

In [3]:
gauss = lambda q,a,c: a*np.random.randn(2, q) + np.transpose(np.tile(c, (q,1)))
X = np.random.randn(2,n)*.3
Y = np.hstack((gauss(int(m/2),.5,[0,1.6]),np.hstack((gauss(int(m/4),.3,[-1,-1]),gauss(int(m/4),.3,[1,-1])))))

Generate the weights a,ba,b.

In [4]:
normalize = lambda a: a/np.sum(a)
a = normalize(np.random.rand(n, 1))
b = normalize(np.random.rand(m, 1))

Helper function for display of clouds.

myplot = lambda x,y,ms,col: plt.scatter(x,y, s=ms*20, edgecolors="k", c=col, linewidths=2)

Display the point clouds. The size of each dot is proportional to its probability density weight.

Compute the cost matrix Ci,j:=∥xi−xj∥2Ci,j:=‖xi−xj‖2.

In [7]:
def distmat(x,y):
    return np.sum(x**2,0)[:,None] + np.sum(y**2,0)[None,:] - 2*x.transpose().dot(y)
C = distmat(X,Y)

Define the optimiztion variable PP.

In [8]:
P = cp.Variable((n,m))

Define the set of discrete couplings between αα and ββ

U(a,b):={P∈Rn×m+,∀i,∑jPi,j=ai,∀j,∑iPi,j=bj}.U(a,b):={P∈R+n×m,∀i,∑jPi,j=ai,∀j,∑iPi,j=bj}.

In [9]:
u = np.ones((m,1))
v = np.ones((n,1))
U = [0 <= P, cp.matmul(P,u)==a, cp.matmul(P.T,v)==b]

The Kantorovitch formulation of the optimal transport reads

P⋆∈argminP∈U(a,b)∑i,jPi,jCi,j.P⋆∈argminP∈U(a,b)∑i,jPi,jCi,j.
Solve it using CVXPY

In [10]:
objective = cp.Minimize( cp.sum(cp.multiply(P,C)) )
prob = cp.Problem(objective, U)
result = prob.solve()

An optimal coupling P⋆P⋆ can be shown to be a sparse matrix with less than n+m−1n+m−1 non zero entries. An entry P⋆i,j≠0Pi,j⋆≠0 should be understood as a link between xixi and yjyj where an amount of mass equal to P⋆i,jPi,j⋆ is transfered.

Check that the number of non-zero entries in P⋆P⋆ is n+m−1n+m−1. Beware that we are using an interior point method here, so that entries of P⋆P⋆ are nevery exactly 0.

In [11]:
print("Number of non-zero: %d (n + m-1 = %d)" %(len(P.value[P.value>1e-5]), n + m-1))

Number of non-zero: 138 (n + m-1 = 139)

plt.show()

Displacement Interpolation¶

For any t∈[0,1]t∈[0,1], one can define a distribution μtμt such that t↦μtt↦μt defines a geodesic for the Wasserstein metric.

Since the W2W2 distance is a geodesic distance, this geodesic path solves the following variational problem

μt=argminμ(1−t)W2(α,μ)2+tW2(β,μ)2.μt=argminμ(1−t)W2(α,μ)2+tW2(β,μ)2.

This can be understood as a generalization of the usual Euclidean barycenter to barycenter of distribution. Indeed, in the case that α=δxα=δx and β=δyβ=δy, one has μt=δxtμt=δxt where xt=(1−t)x+tyxt=(1−t)x+ty.

Once the optimal coupling P⋆P⋆ has been computed, the interpolated distribution is obtained as

μt=∑i,jP⋆i,jδ(1−t)xi+tyj.μt=∑i,jPi,j⋆δ(1−t)xi+tyj.

Find the i,ji,j with non-zero P⋆i,jPi,j⋆.

In [14]:
I,J = np.nonzero(P.value>1e-5)
Pij = P.value[I,J]

Display the evolution of μtμt for a varying value of t∈[0,1]t∈[0,1].

In [15]:
plt.figure(figsize =(15,10))
tlist = np.linspace(0, 1, 6)
for i in range(len(tlist)):
    t = tlist[i]
    Xt = (1-t)*X[:,I] + t*Y[:,J]
    plt.subplot(2,3,i+1)
    plt.axis("off")
    for j in range(len(Pij)):

    plt.title("t = %.1f" %t) 
    plt.xlim(np.min(Y[0,:])-.1,np.max(Y[0,:])+.1)
    plt.ylim(np.min(Y[1,:])-.1,np.max(Y[1,:])+.1)
plt.show()

Optimal Assignement¶

In the case where n=mn=m and the weights are uniform ai=1/n,bj=1/nai=1/n,bj=1/n, one can show that there is at least one optimal transport coupling which is actually a permutation matrix. This properties comes from the fact that the extremal point of the polytope U(1,1)U(1,1) are permutation matrices.

This means that there exists an optimal permutation σ⋆∈Σnσ⋆∈Σn such that

P⋆i,j={1ifj=σ⋆(i),0otherwise.Pi,j⋆={1ifj=σ⋆(i),0otherwise.

where ΣnΣn is the set of permutation (bijections) of {1,…,n}{1,…,n}.

This permutation thus solves the so-called optimal assignement problem

σ⋆∈argminσ∈Σn∑iCi,σ(j).σ⋆∈argminσ∈Σn∑iCi,σ(j).

Use the same number of points.
